        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We aim to map the molecular gas within the bar region of NGC1365 using a survey approach similar to PAWS to resolve massive clouds, construct GMC mass spectra for the different environments and performed a detailed kinematic analysis.

Spectral Setup: We target the CO(2-1) line at a spectral resolution of 0.6 km/s (after Hanning smoothing) for a bandwidth of 1200 km/s. These requirements are sufficient to easily access the full velocity extent of NGC 1365 as indicated by HI observations (Jorsater &amp; van Moorsel 1995).

Resolution and ACA: We target a resolution of 0.5" = 45 pc at NGC1365's distance (D = 18.6 Mpc, Madore et al. 1999). This will allow us to isolate individual clouds in order to measure their mass functions and to resolve massive GMCs as in PAWS. The cloud-scale resolution will also allow for a detailed kinematic study of the gas motion, in particular, we will be able to resolve sites of potential shocks and inflow motion across the stellar bar, reaching close to the AGN itself. Previous low resolution CO observations of NGC1365 have provided evidence for an extended and diffuse component of molecular gas associated with the bar (e.g. Das &amp; Jog 1995). This gravitationally unbound gas could originate from the shear induced by the bar that disperses the outer layers of GMCs. To correctly access this gas component we therefore require ACA.

Coverage: The targeted area of 215x80" (or ~20x7 kpc) has been chosen to map the full bar region and the bar's tips to extrapolate the required kinematic information. Moreover, the large field is essential to obtain statistically significant samples of cloud populations per environment, as shown by PAWS, in order to pose firm conclusions about the average properties of the GMC populations and to construct reliable mass spectra. In particular the redundancy of environments (e.g. both bar sides) is important to test subtle trends - a lesson learned from PAWS (Colombo et al. 2013a).
The goal requires 132 12m array pointings and 47 7m array pointings.

Sensitivity: We target a sensitivity of 0.5 K per 5 km/s channel width in order to achieve a signal-to-noise (&gt;10) sufficient to reliably measure the properties of massive clouds. Considering a peak brightness temperature of 3 K of a GMC filling the beam (Solomon et al. 1987, Bolatto et al. 2008, Colombo et al. 2013a) and an aCO=2.6 Mo (K km/s pc^2)^{-1} (Tabatabaei et al. 2013), this will allow us to access a 5sigma cloud of 8.5x10^4 Mo per 5 km/s similar to the point-mass resolution of PAWS.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
